 cultural orientations, charging it with norms and values, hopes and fears. And it is memory that links the present to the past and therefore has to be seen as the most fundamental procedure of the human mind that constitutes history: memory and historical thinking are the door of the human mind to experience. At the same time, it transforms the past into a meaningful and sense bearing part of the present and beyond. It is these complex interrelationships that are the focus of the contributors to this volume, among them such distinguished scholars as Paul Ricoeur, Johan Galtung, Eberhard Lämmert, and James E. Young. Full of profound insights into human society pat and present it is a book that not only historians but also philosophers and social scientists should engage with.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 0aCollective memory. 0aHistoryxPhilosophy. 7aHISTORY / Historiography.2bisacsh1 aAnkersmit, Frank R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAssmann, Aleida, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarasch, Moshe, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarr, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCavalli, Alessandro, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDux, Günter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGaltung, Johan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHoffmann, Detlef, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLämmert, Eberhard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRicoeur, Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRüsen, Jörn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRüsen, Jörn, e